{
  "texts": [
    "Selected examples of studies employing the Fourier-based method are Poindexter et al. (2008), Chartas et al. (2009), Dai et al. (2010), MacLeod et al. (2015), Morgan et al. (2018), Cornachione et al. (2020a).",
    "Apart from GPUD's direct approach to inverse ray-shooting, the tree and polygon based algorithms can also benefit from the massive GPU parallelization, at the cost of more complex algorithm development.",
    "A spectacular example is the Teralens foot_1 algorithm, which follows the same general principles as the tree code of Wambsganss (1999) but has a dramatically different algorithmic design tuned for maximum parallel efficiency.",
    "One can also envisage merging the tree-based method that approximates the lens deflections with shooting polygons instead of rays, since the two approximate different parts of the lens equation.",
    "Recently, Jiménez-Vicente and Mediavilla (2022) achieved this by combining the inverse polygon method with the fast multiple method (Greencard and Rokhlin 1987), an algorithm similar in concept to a tree or particle-mesh algorithm."
  ]
}